{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1622623-f626-43e4-a83c-a117883002fd","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **Speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s specifically:**\n\n- Use `kubectl cp` to copy the `.nettrace` file out of the pod.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or an **ephemeral debug container**: `kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 --target=<container>`\n- For very high CPU, prefer **`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`** first to confirm it's CPU-bound (vs. threadpool starvation, etc.).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"495ccd34-0ba9-4e45-ba1f-3a9cfe350ee8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"6817:F913:A29B3D9:B1B3FBD:69FD3C37"},"id":"1d54a34e-d6c7-4098-955a-4a04ce5080b3","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:28:32.225Z","parentId":"eb9c02cf-6ac3-4ab4-a096-d0c05e08b7df"}
